<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Padding in CSS3</title>


<style type="text/css">
.box1 {
	border: 2px solid CadetBlue;
	background-color: Gainsboro;
}
.box {
	border: 2px solid CadetBlue;
	background-color: Gainsboro;
	padding-top: 5px;
	padding-right: 10px;
	padding-bottom: 5px;
	padding-left: 10px;
}

.box2 {
	border: 2px solid CadetBlue;
	background-color: Gainsboro;
	width: 100px;
	height: 100px;
	margin: 10px;
}

.box3 {
	border: 2px solid CadetBlue;
	background-color: Gainsboro;
	width: 100px;
	height: 100px;
	padding: 1em;
	margin: 10px;
}
</style>

</head>

<body>
<h3>Padding</h3>
<h4>padding is an inner, invisible border around your element</h4>
<h4>By default, most block level elements have zero padding, meaning that text and other content will go all the way to the edge of the parent element</h4>

<div class="box1">
	Hello, world!
</div>

<h4>padding properties are : padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom and padding-left</h4>

<div class="box">
	Hello, world!
</div>

<h4>Using Padding shorthand properties</h4>
<div class="box2" style="padding: 10px 10px 10px 10px;">
	Box
</div>

<h4>Using Relative Padding</h4>
<div class="box3" style="font-size: 1em;">
	Box
</div>

<div class="box3" style="font-size: 2em;">
	Box
</div>

<div class="box3" style="font-size: 3em;">
	Box
</div>
<footer>

